#![recursion_limit = "1024"]
//! fat-station — native HTTP server that hosts a NativeLlamaPipeline
//! against a locally-mmap'd .knot file and exposes the same wire contract
//! as the CF Worker layer / cobordism stations.
//!
//! References:
//!   - Default LLM: Qwen2.5-Coder (arXiv 2409.12186) /
//!     Qwen2.5 (arXiv 2412.15115). https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.12186
//!   - Cobordism / Frobenius merge for vocab sharding: Atiyah, "Topological
//!     quantum field theories" (Publ. Math. IHÉS, 1988); Segal 1988.
//!     Locally cited at `open-source/gnosis/FORMAL_LEDGER.md`
//!     §2 "Atiyah-Segal TQFT Functor on Full Cob_1 (State Merging)".
//!

//! Why this exists
//! ----------------
//! The deployed CF Workers are capped at 128 MiB resident memory. The qwen-
//! coder-7b knot contains ~880 MiB of layer weights per 14-layer station and
//! ~447 MiB of `output_weight`, which forces "fluid memory" gymnastics
//! (R2-Range fetch + set_tensor + evict per phase) that may be racing with
//! the wasm-bindgen recursive-call panic seen in production. This binary
//! cuts that variable: every tensor is held resident via mmap, and we hit
//! the same `forward_range_chunk` / `lm_head_only` / `embed_chunk` /
//! `embed_chunk_range` paths that the JS Pipeline drives in production.
//!
//! If the wasm-bindgen "recursive use of an object" panic also reproduces
//! here, the bug lives in the Rust kernel and not in the wasm wrapping
//! layer. If it does NOT reproduce, the bug is wasm-bindgen-specific and
//! probably tied to the eviction race in `fluidForwardRange`.
//!
//! Wire contract (mirrors `open-source/gnosis/distributed-inference-host/src/station.ts`)
//! ----------------------------------------------------------------------
//! GET  /health                         -> JSON {status, role, layers, vocab}
//! GET  /.aeon/attention-closure-benchmark
//!                                     -> JSON optimizer-admission certificate
//! POST /embed                          (entry only)
//!     headers: X-Position, X-Token-Count, X-Request-Id
//!     body:    Uint32Array tokens (raw little-endian u32 bytes)
//!     reply:   Float32Array residual (raw f32 bytes)
//! POST /forward
//!     headers: X-Position, X-Sequence-Length, X-Layer-Range, X-Request-Id
//!     body:    Float32Array residual
//!     reply:   Float32Array residual
//! POST /lm-head                        (exit only)
//!     headers: X-Sequence-Length, X-Request-Id
//!     body:    Float32Array residual
//!     reply:   Float32Array logits (vocab_size)
//! POST /sample-next                    (exit only)
//!     headers: X-Sequence-Length, X-Request-Id
//!     body:    Float32Array residual
//!     reply:   JSON { token_id }
//! POST /decode-next                    (single native station only)
//!     headers: X-Token, X-Position, X-Request-Id
//!              optional: X-FFN-Leakage-Mode, X-FFN-Guard-Admit-Weather-Cells,
//!              X-FFN-Guard-Speculate-Weather-Cells, X-FFN-Guard-Deny-Weather-Cells,
//!              X-FFN-Predictive-Min-Gate-Up-Skip-Blocks,
//!              X-FFN-Guard-Min-Logit-Margin,
//!              X-FFN-Guard-High-Confidence-Logit-Margin,
//!              X-FFN-Guard-RMS-Delta3-Threshold
//!     body:    empty
//!     reply:   JSON { token_id }
//! POST /cobordism-embed                (cobordism only)
//!     headers: X-Position, X-Token-Count, X-Vocab-Start, X-Vocab-End, X-Request-Id
//!     body:    Uint32Array tokens
//!     reply:   Float32Array partial embeddings (zero outside the shard's vocab range)
//! POST /tokenize                       (any role)
//!     body:    JSON { text: string, add_bos?: bool }
//!     reply:   JSON { tokens: u32[], count, add_bos }
//!     note:    in-tree smoke-table only; unknown text -> 400. See
//!              `qwen2_tokenize_smoke_prompt` for the recognized set.
//! POST /detokenize                     (any role)
//!     body:    JSON { token_ids: u32[] }  (also accepts { tokens: u32[] })
//!     reply:   JSON { text: string, count, source }
//!     note:    full-vocab when TOKENIZER_GGUF_PATH points at a Qwen2 GGUF
//!              (loads tokenizer.ggml.tokens, mirrors openai-server.ts);
//!              otherwise a tiny reverse smoke table (unknown id -> 400).
//!              See `handle_detokenize`.
//! POST /prompt-feedback                (any role)
//!     body:    JSON { frames_base64: string[], max_frames?: number }
//!     reply:   JSON { context: string | null, line_count, theorem }
//!
//! Roles:
//!   entry      - serves /embed + /forward
//!   mid        - serves /forward
//!   exit       - serves /forward + /lm-head
//!   both       - serves /embed + /forward + /lm-head (single-station deploys)
//!   cobordism  - serves /cobordism-embed only
//!
//! Single-forward prefill (verified on qwen-coder-7b, role=both)
//! -------------------------------------------------------------
//! The whole prompt prefills in ONE /forward instead of N /decode-next
//! calls. For the PARIS prompt [785,6722,315,9625,374] (seq=5, dense
//! Qwen2.5-Coder-7B, hidden=3584, vocab=152064) the chain below yields
//! next-token 12095 (" Paris") in a single ~11 s cold forward (vs five
//! sequential /decode-next). All bodies are raw little-endian; headers
//! are exact:
//!
//!   1. POST /tokenize  {"text":"The capital of France is"}
//!        -> {"tokens":[785,6722,315,9625,374],"count":5,"add_bos":false}
//!   2. POST /embed     header X-Position: 0
//!        body  = 5 * u32 LE  (20 bytes)            [token ids]
//!        reply = 5*3584 f32 LE (71680 bytes)       [embeddings, row-major]
//!   3. POST /forward   headers X-Position: 0, X-Sequence-Length: 5,
//!                              X-Layer-Range: 0-28   (NOTE: dash, not "..")
//!        body  = the 71680-byte embedding buffer from step 2
//!        reply = 71680-byte residual (same [seq, hidden] shape)
//!   4a. POST /lm-head  header X-Sequence-Length: 5
//!        body  = the 71680-byte residual from step 3
//!        reply = 152064 f32 LE (608256 bytes) — logits for the LAST
//!                position only (argmax = 12095, logit 14.514)
//!   4b. POST /sample-next  header X-Sequence-Length: 5
//!        body  = same residual
//!        reply = {"token_id":12095,"elapsed_ms":...}
//!   5. POST /detokenize {"token_ids":[12095]} -> {"text":" Paris",...}
//!
//! /embed and /forward mutate the pipeline KV cache (X-Position is the
//! cache write offset); a second run with a warm cache short-circuits
//! /forward to ~0 ms. /lm-head and /sample-next read only the last row,
//! so the lm-head reply is one vocab row, not seq*vocab.
//!
//! CLI:
//!   fat-station --knot PATH --port N --role {entry|mid|exit|both|cobordism}
//!               --layers START..END
//!               [--vocab START..END]   (cobordism only)
//!
//! Notes:
//!   - Wraps `NativeLlamaPipeline` from `model.rs`. The pipeline is shared
//!     across requests via a `Mutex<Pipeline>` because the kernel is not
//!     `Sync` (per-call mutable scratch buffers + the KV cache). Concurrent
//!     requests serialize on the mutex; for a local fat station serving one
//!     mesh peer at a time this is the right shape.
//!   - We do NOT clamp the kv cache (KV_MAX_SEQ_LEN=2048 native default).

